  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - CLERIC</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>CARNA'S GUIDE TO A HEALTHY ENCHANTER</font> - <small>Carna, Fennin Ro</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>
<p>Please be nice to your enchanter since he is the difference between success and a group slaughter. Too many times I've seen a dead enchanters while the rest of the group lives due to poor cleric preparation.  I'm writing this from my point of view an what I've found to work during my travels through the low to mid 50's.<br>
<br>
BUFFS<br>
<br>
Heroism (lvl 52) and Symbol of Marzin/Naltron (lvl 54/44): At level 55 these two buffs provide an extra 1025 hp's (less for Naltron), essentially doubling the hit points the enchanter would have.  The enchanter will typically have self buffed themselves with Rune for the really tough areas.  Always keep a both of these up on your enchanter.<br>
<br>
Death Pact (lvl 51) and is a nice insurance policy to use when breaking into a high risk area.  I keep it active as long as I feel there is substantial risk for the enchanter, like in the planes.<br>
<br>
HEALING STRATEGY<br>
<br>
At 55 I have two primary spells I keep up for everyone. Remedy (lvl 51) heals 433 to 438 in 3.0 seconds, and Divine Light (lvl 53) to heal 880 to 910 in 4.5 seconds.  When the enchanter is needed to mez mobs I use this general rule: a single extra mob - immediate cast of Remedy on any sign of damage, and with two or more extra mobs - immediate cast of Divine Light on any sign of damage.  I'm not concerned with the extra
manna use from Divine Light as I'd rather over heal than under heal.  I've been in situations where chain casting Remedy isn't quick enough to keep an enchanter alive.  I will always heal an enchanter before anyone else in the party, and always keep their hit points topped off.<br>
<br>
UTILITY SPELLS<br>
<br>
Stun (lvl 5): I cannot say enough about this one.  This is our only stun that will not break an enchanter mez.  During a difficult mez or mez break it is handy to /assist your enchanter and stun that mob to help avoid an interruption.<br>
<br>
Atone (lvl 34): you can reduce potential damage to an enchanter by casting this on one or two mez'd mobs so they won't
agro on the enchanter when it breaks.  This is a much lower manna spell than memory flux and works almost as well.<br>
<br>
Divine Aura (lvl 1): Standing and taking a beating is one of the best ways you can help your enchanter.  With your higher AC you can take damage longer and give the enchanter a chance to mez.  If your hit points get too low just DA and keep the mob entertained.<br>
<br>
OTHER NOTES<br>
<br>
I always have the enchanter targeted when sitting idle meditating.  One never knows when a train will visit, and by avoiding the extra step of targeting the enchanter during confusion can save a few lives.  If you do happen to lose an enchanter, or anyone in your party for that matter, please ask them to beg a copper from someone near them before you rez them.  There's nothing worse than having naked corpse decay.<br>
<br>
Thanks to Iumar helping me learn and test this strategy.<br>
<br>
<br>
</p>
</td></tr>
